                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d221">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8827: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-20T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 20, 1947—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>130. Your 258, July 19, 3 p.m., and 256, July 18, 3 p.m., paragraph 3. Department
                    continues to hold the view expressed in its 116, July 13, 7 p.m.</p>
                <pb facs="0233" n="226" xml:id="pg_226"/>
                <p>On July 18 the Chinese Ambassador here, in response to an oral inquiry, expressed
                    personal opinion that it was preferable that you remain at Peiping.</p>
                <p>Please continue to keep the Department informed of developments and of your views
                    in this regard.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
